2026-04-21 01:26:57 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 6 (positive line conduction path / internal series conductor, likely missing or miswired after LED removal)'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that up to Control Module 5 the chain carries a solid 12 V with correct polarity. With everything connected, the potential on the supposed positive line collapses to ~0.03 V starting at the output of Module 6, while the negative line stays near the same potential, indicating that the positive path is effectively open there.\n\nWhen Module 6 is isolated, its input terminals still see a correct 12 V and 0 V, and there is no short between them, so the issue is not external cabling or a load-side short. Internal testing of Module 6 shows:\n- Input + to output + is essentially an open circuit (~7.17×10¹¹ Ω) even with the switch ON.\n- Input − to output − is a low-resistance path (~0.1 Ω), as expected.\n- The indicator LED/resistor assembly is physically missing.\n\nIn a healthy control module, the input and output of each rail must be directly connected (through the switch on the positive side) so that the series chain is continuous. The open circuit on the positive rail inside Module 6 breaks the series path and explains why 12 V is not seen beyond this point and why the lamp never energizes. The missing LED/resistor and associated rework very likely interrupted the positive conductor or the switch-to-output link.\n\nThus the root cause is an internal open circuit in the positive conduction path of Control Module 6; repairing or replacing that module (or restoring the internal positive connection) should restore operation of the downstream modules and the load.'
